statement.p:
Consider the linear system
\begin{alignedat}{4} x \amp {}+{} \amp 2y \amp {}-{} \amp z \amp {}={} \amp 1 \\ 3x \amp {}+{} \amp 2y \amp {}+{} \amp 2z \amp {}={} \amp 7 \\ -x \amp \amp \amp {}+{} \amp 4z \amp {}={} \amp -3 \\ \end{alignedat}
Write this system as an augmented matrix and use Sage to find a description of the solution space.

solution.p:
We can use Sage to find the reduced row echelon form of the corresponding augmented matrix:
\left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 1 \\ 3 \amp 2 \amp 2 \amp 7 \\ -2 \amp 0 \amp 4 \amp -3 \\ \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrr|r} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
This shows that there is exactly one solution (3,-1,0).

li.p:
Let's now look at another traffic pattern.
In this case, we find the equations:
\begin{alignedat}{5} x \amp {}+{} \amp y \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp {}={} \amp 650 \\ x \amp \amp \amp {}-{} \amp z \amp \amp \amp {}={} \amp -150 \\ \amp \amp y \amp \amp \amp {}+{} \amp w \amp {}={} \amp 580 \\ \amp \amp \amp \amp z \amp {}-{} \amp w \amp {}={} \amp 220\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}
This gives the augmented matrix:
\left[\begin{array}{rrrr|r} 1 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 650 \\ 1 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 0 \amp -150 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 580 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 220 \end{array}\right] \sim \left[\begin{array}{rrrrr} 1 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -1 \amp 70 \\ 0 \amp 1 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp 580 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \amp -1 \amp 220 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \end{array}\right]\text{.}
Here, we may view w as a free variable and write
\begin{alignedat}{3} x \amp {}={} \amp 70 + w \\ y \amp {}={} \amp 580 - w \\ z \amp {}={} \amp 220 + w\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}
This shows that there are infinitely many solutions. This makes sense since the unknown flows x, y, z, and w form a loop. For instance, we can add one car to each of x, z, and w provided we remove one from y.
Since we must have y\geq 0, it follows that the free variable w satisfies 0\leq w \leq 580. This means that x satisfies 70 \leq x \leq 650.

There are infinitely many solutions described by 

  \begin{alignedat}{3}
  x \amp {}={} \amp 70 + w \\
  y \amp {}={} \amp 580 - w \\
  z \amp {}={} \amp 220 + w\text{.} \\
  \end{alignedat}

solution.p:
We set up the equations
\begin{alignedat}{7} 4T_1 \amp {}-{} \amp T_2 \amp \amp \amp {}-{} \amp T_4 \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp {}={} \amp 25 \\ -T_1 \amp {}+{} \amp 4T_2 \amp {}-{} \amp T_3 \amp \amp \amp{}-{} \amp T_5 \amp \amp \amp {}={} \amp 20 \\ \amp \amp -T_2 \amp {}+{} \amp 4T_3 \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp {}-{} \amp T_6 \amp {}={} \amp 55 \\ -T_1 \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp {}{}+ \amp 4T_4 \amp {}-{} \amp T_5 \amp \amp \amp {}={} \amp 20 \\ \amp \amp -T_2 \amp \amp \amp {}-{} \amp T_4 \amp {}+{} \amp 4T_5 \amp {}-{} \amp T_6 \amp {}={} \amp 20 \\ \amp \amp \amp \amp -T_3 \amp \amp \amp {}-{} \amp T_5 \amp {}+{} \amp 4T_6 \amp {}={} \amp 70\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}
Setting up an augmented matrix and using Sage to find its reduced row echelon form, we obtain
\begin{array}{rrr} T_1 = 14.86, \amp T_2 = 20.50, \amp T_3 = 26.19 \\ T_4 = 13.95, \amp T_5 = 20.93, \amp T_6 = 29.28\text{.} \\ \end{array}

li.p:
Writing equations for the amount of charcoal and the amount of potassium nitrate, we have
\begin{alignedat}{3} 0.6x \amp {}+{} \amp 0.5y \amp {}={} \amp 100.3 \\ 0.3x \amp {}+{} \amp 0.2y \amp {}={} \amp 46.9\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}
Solving this gives x=113 pounds and y=65 pounds.

We will equate the number of hydrogen and oxygen atoms before and after the reaction.
Before the reaction, there are two hydrogen atoms for every hydrogen molecule. Since there are x hydrogen molecules, we have 2x hydrogen atoms before the reaction.
After the reaction, there are two hydrogen atoms for every water molecule. Since there are z hydrogen molecules, we have 2z hydrogen atoms after the reaction. This gives the equation 2x=2z.
Similarly, there are 2y oxygen atoms before the reaction and z oxygen atoms after. This gives the equation 2y = z.
We have the linear system
\begin{alignedat}{4} 2x \amp \amp \amp {}-{} \amp 2z \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\ \amp \amp 2y \amp {}-{} \amp z \amp {}={} \amp 0\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}
When we create the augmented matrix and find its reduced row echelon form, we see that z is a free variable so that
\begin{alignedat}{2} x \amp {}={} \amp z \\ y \amp {}={} \amp \frac12 z\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}
We need all the quantities to be integers, and the smallest value of z that makes y an integer is z=2. Therefore, we have x=2, y=1, and z=2. The reaction is then
2\thinspace \text{H}_2 + \thinspace\text{O}_2 \to 2\thinspace \text{H}_2\text{O}\text{.}

Proceeding as in the previous part, we have
\begin{alignedat}{8} \text{K:} \amp \thinspace \amp x_1 \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp {}-{} \amp 2x_5 \amp \amp \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\ \text{Mn:} \amp \thinspace \amp x_1 \amp {}+{} \amp x_2 \amp \amp \amp {}-{} \amp x_4 \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\ \text{O:} \amp \thinspace \amp 4x_1 \amp {}+{} \amp 4x_2 \amp {}+{} \amp x_3 \amp {}-{} \amp 2x_4 \amp {}-{} \amp 4x_5 \amp {}-{} \amp 4x_6 \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\ \text{S:} \amp \thinspace \amp \amp \amp x_2 \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp {}-{} \amp x_5 \amp {}-{} \amp x_6 \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\ \text{H:} \amp \thinspace \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp 2x_3 \amp \amp \amp \amp \amp {}-{} \amp 2x_6 \amp {}= \amp 0\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}
Solving this linear system, we find
\begin{alignedat}{2} x_1 \amp {}={} \amp x_6 \\ x_2 \amp {}={} \amp \frac32 x_6 \\ x_3 \amp {}={} \amp x_6 \\ x_4 \amp {}={} \amp \frac52 x_6 \\ x_5 \amp {}={} \amp \frac12 x_6\text{.} \\ \end{alignedat}
Once again, we choose x_6 to be the smallest positive integer that causes all of the variables to be integers. This means that x_6 = 2 so that we have
\begin{array}{rrr} x_1 = 2, \amp x_2 = 3, \amp x_3 = 2, \\ x_4 = 5, \amp x_5 = 1, \amp x_6 = 2\text{.} \\ \end{array}
This gives the reaction:
2\thinspace \text{K}\text{Mn}\text{O}_4 + 3\thinspace \text{Mn}\text{S}\text{O}_4 + 2\thinspace \text{H}_2\text{O} \to 5\thinspace \text{Mn}\text{O}_2 + \thinspace \text{K}_2\text{S}\text{O}_4 + 2\thinspace \text{H}_2\text{S}\text{O}_4.

The exact solution is

  x=9, y=-36, z=30\text{.}

However, if we compute with only 10 bits, we find the
approximate solution

  x=8.9, y=-35, z=29\text{.}
